\begin_layout Standard
Given any nonzero vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left\langle \mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2}-\frac{\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}{\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}\mathbf{b}_{1}\right\rangle  & =\left\langle \mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2}\right\rangle -\left\langle \mathbf{b}_{1},\frac{\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}{\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}\mathbf{b}_{1}\right\rangle \nonumber \\
 & =\left\langle \mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2}\right\rangle -\frac{\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}{\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}\left\langle \mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\right\rangle \nonumber \\
 & =\left\langle \mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2}\right\rangle -\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle\nonumber \\
 & =0\label{eq:Gram-Schmidt-first-step}
\end{align}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}-\frac{\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}{\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 are always orthogonal (even if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

 are not).
 This applies in any inner product space, not just 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}{\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is called the component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 direction or the (orthogonal) 
\series bold
projection
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

, and is often denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{proj}_{\mathbf{b}_{1}}\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Subtracting this term from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

 removes the component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 direction, leaving only the component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

 orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 (not in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

).
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, this is seen geometrically in the following diagram.
