\begin_layout Standard
A set of three nonzero vectors, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{3}$
\end_inset

, can be orthogonalized by extending the process to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Its components in the directions of both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}-\frac{\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}{\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 will need to be subtracted.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}_{1}=\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}_{2}=\mathbf{b}_{2}-\text{proj}_{\mathbf{w}_{1}}\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}_{3}=\mathbf{b}_{3}-\text{proj}_{\mathbf{w}_{1}}\mathbf{b}_{3}-\text{proj}_{\mathbf{w}_{2}}\mathbf{b}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 For larger sets, the process continues recursively.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{w}_{1} & =\mathbf{b}_{1}\nonumber \\
\mathbf{w}_{j} & =\mathbf{b}_{j}-\text{proj}_{\mathbf{w}_{1}}\mathbf{b}_{j}-\text{proj}_{\mathbf{w}_{2}}\mathbf{b}_{j}-\cdots-\text{proj}_{\mathbf{w}_{j-1}}\mathbf{b}_{j},\quad j=2,3,\ldots,n.\label{eq:orthogonalization}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The process as described by (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:orthogonalization"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is called 
\series bold
orthogonalization
\series default
, or Gram-Schmidt orthogonalization.
\end_layout

